tant sites from this era.<ref name=PHARR-NPS>{{Cite web|title=Pharr Mounds-National Register of Historic Places Indian Mounds of Mississippi Travel Itinerary|publisher=National Park Service|url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/travel/mounds/pha.htm|accessdate=2010-11-16}}</ref> |- | [[Portsmouth Earthworks]] || [[File:Portsmouth Works Group A B C D Squier and Davis 01.jpg|125px|Portsmouth Earthworks]] || The Portsmouth Earthworks is a large mound complex constructed by the [[Hopewell tradition#Ohio Hopewell culture|Ohio Hopewell culture]] (100 BCE to 500 CE).<ref name="ohiohistorycentral.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.ohiohistorycentral.org/entry.php?rec=2222|title=Portsmouth Earthworks-Ohio History Central|accessdate =2009-06-06}}</ref> The site was one of the largest ceremonial centers constructed by the Hopewell and is located at the confluence of the [[Scioto River|Scioto]] and [[Ohio River]]s. The majority of the site is now covered by the city of [[Portsmouth, Ohio|Portsmouth]] in [[Scioto County, Ohio]].<ref name="ohiohistorycentral.org"/> |- | [[Renner Village Archeological Site]] || || The Renner Village Archeological Site is a significant [[Kansas City Hopewell]] culture archaeological site located in the municipality of [[Riverside, Missouri]]. Known by archaeologists as the Renner site(23PL1), the site contains [[Hopewell tradition|Hopewell]] and [[Mississippian culture|Middle Mississippian]] artifacts. The site is one of a several Kansas City Hopewell sites near the junction of [[Line Creek (Missouri)|Line Creek]] and the [[Missouri River]].<ref>{{Cite web|url= http://users.stlcc.edu/mfuller/renner/|title=Renner Site 23PL1|accessdate =2009-10-09}}</ref> |- | [[Seip Earthworks and Dill Mounds District]] || [[File:Seip Earthworks Hopewell Culture NHP NPS.jpg|125px|Seip Earthworks and Dill Mounds District]] || A large hilltop enclosure in [[Ross County, Ohio]]. |- | [[Serpent Mounds Park]] || || Not to be confused with the [[Serpent Mound]] in [[Adams County, Ohio]], the site was constructed by the [[Point Peninsula Complex]] peoples, a Hopewellian people who lived in central and southeastern [[Ontario]], southwestern [[Quebec]], and northern parts [[New York state]] between 300 BCE and 700 CE. |- | [[Sinnissippi Mounds]] || [[File:Sterling Il Sinnissippi Site5.jpg|125px|Sinnissippi Mounds]] || The Sinnissippi Mounds are a [[Havana Hopewell culture]] burial mound grouping located in the city of [[Sterling, Illinois]], [[United States]]. |- | [[Toolesboro Mound Group]] || [[File:Toolesboro mounds.jpg|125px|Toolesboro Mound Group]] || A [[Havana Hopewell culture]] site, The Toolesboro Mound Group is a group of mounds on the north bank of the [[Iowa River]] near its discharge into the [[Mississippi River|Mississippi]]. The mounds are owned and displayed to the public by the [[State Historical Society of Iowa]]. The mound group is located east of [[Wapello, Iowa]], near the unincorporated community of [[Toolesboro, Iowa|Toolesboro]]. |- | [[Tremper Mound and Works]] || [[File:Tremper Mound Squier and Davis 01.jpg|125px|Tremper Mound and Works]] || The Tremper Mound and Works are an [[Hopewell tradition|Ohio Hopewell]] (100 BCE to 500 CE) earthen enclosure and large, irregularly shaped mound. It was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 1972. The site is located in [[Scioto County, Ohio]], about five miles northwest of [[Portsmouth, Ohio]], on the second terrace floodplain overlooking the [[Scioto River]]. |- | [[Trowbridge Archeological Site]] || || The '''Trowbridge Archaeological Site''' is located in the vicinity of North 61st Street and Leavenworth Road in [[Kansas City, Kansas]]. It was inhabited c. 200–600 CE by the [[Kansas City Hopewell]] culture. |- |}
