{{Infobox artwork | image_file = File:Orazio Gentileschi - Il suonatore di liuto (National Gallery of Art).jpg | painting_alignment = Front | image_size = 285px | title = The Lute Player | alt = | artist = [[Orazio Gentileschi]] | year = c. 1612–1626 | medium = Oil on canvas | height_metric = 100 | width_metric = 74 | length_metric = | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | metric_unit = cm | imperial_unit = in | city = [[Washington, D.C.]], United States | museum = [[National Gallery of Art]] | owner = }}
'''''The Lute Player''''' is a painting from c.&nbsp;1612–1615 by the Italian artist [[Orazio Gentileschi]] (1563–1639) depicting a young woman in a golden dress with a [[lute]].<ref name = "C&M113">{{harvnb|Christiansen|Mann|2002|p=113}}</ref>
==Background==
Gentileschi came into contact with the Italian painter [[Michelangelo Merisi da Caravaggio]] (1571–1610) during Gentileschi's early 1600s Rome period. He adopted Caravaggio's method of painting from life using dramatic lighting and is considered one of the leading ''[[Caravaggisti]]''. Nevertheless, he developed his own lyrical manner using soft, subdued tones.<ref name="CMVII">{{harvnb|Christiansen|Mann|2002|p=VII}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getty.edu/art/exhibitions/gentileschi/|title=Orazio Gentileschi in Genoa: Paintings for the Palazzo Sauli|website=[[The J. Paul Getty Museum]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalgallery.org.uk/artists/orazio-gentileschi|title=Orazio Gentileschi|website=[[The National Gallery]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artic.edu/exhibition/fourfollowerscaravaggio|title=Four Followers of Caravaggio|website=[[Art Institute of Chicago]]}}</ref>
==Description== ''The Lute Player'' depicts a young woman in a golden dress with a [[lute]], turned away from the observer, concentrating her attention on the nineteen [[stringed instrument]] and listening intently to a note. She may be tuning her lute in anticipation of a concert, as shown by the assortment of recorders, a cornetto and violin, and the [[song book]]s lying open on the table before her.<ref name=NGA>{{cite web|url=http://www.nga.gov/content/ngaweb/Collection/art-object-page.46434.html|title=The Lute Player|website=[[National Gallery of Art]]}}</ref> The painting is rich in its renderings of fabrics.<ref name="NGA"/> It can be taken as a [[genre scene]] or as a portrait, but since many of the paintings of its time included some allegorical message, it can also represent the [[allegory]] of hearing or a portrayal of [[Harmonia (mythology)|Harmonia]], the [[Greek goddess]] of [[harmony]] and concord.
==Influences== [[File:The Lute Player-Caravaggio (Hermitage).jpg|thumbnail|Caravaggio, ''[[The Lute Player (Caravaggio)|The Lute Player]]'', c. 1600, [[Hermitage Museum]]]]
''The Lute Player'' is influenced by Caravaggio's early genre scenes, especially Caravaggio's own c.&nbsp;1600 painting of the same name in the [[Hermitage Museum]].<ref name="NGA"/> In turn, Gentileschi's painting was the inspiration for [[Giuseppe Crespi|Giuseppe Crespi's]] c.&nbsp;1700–1705 ''[[:File:Crespi, Giuseppe Maria - Frau spielt Laute.jpg|Woman Playing a Lute]]''.<ref name = "C&M113"/> Christiansen & Mann note that Gentileschi returned to Caravaggio's early [[Giorgione]]sque work, exemplified by paintings such as the c.&nbsp;1594–1596 ''[[:File:Penitent Magdalene-Caravaggio (1594-6).jpg|Penitent Magdalene]]'', as guidance for his departure from mainstream Caravaggism that ''The Lute Player'' represents.<ref name="CM114">{{harvnb|Christiansen|Mann|2002|p=114}}</ref>
